Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

## Background and Motivation

While iterating information about an `ILabelSymbol` instance, we have no information if it's a switch case symbol, or a case default label. Also, we cannot specifically filter labels inside a specific switch statement.

## Proposed API

```diff
namespace Microsoft.CodeAnalysis
{
     public interface ILabelSymbol
     {
+        public bool IsSwitchCaseLabel { get; }
+        public bool IsSwitchDefaultLabel { get; }
+        public object? ConstantExpression { get; }
     }
     public class SemanticModel
     {
+        public ImmutableArray<ILabelSymbol> LookupSwitchLabels(int position, object? constantValue);
+        public ILabelSymbol? GetSwitchDefaultLabel(int position);
+        public ImmutableArray<ILabelSymbol> LookupSwitchLabels(SyntaxNode switchStatement, object? constantValue);
+        public ILabelSymbol? GetSwitchDefaultLabel(SyntaxNode switchStatement);
     }
}
```

`IsSwitchCaseLabel` returns true if the label is defined in a `case ...:` syntax inside a switch statement for C#, and `Case X...` syntax for VB. Does not cover the `default` label for C#, or the `Else` label for VB.

`IsSwitchDefaultLabel` returns true if it's the label defined in a `default:` syntax inside a switch statement for C#, or `Else` syntax for VB.

`ConstantExpression` returns the constant expression that the case label matches inside the switch statement. If it's a relational pattern, or a multi-value case label, `null` is returned.

`LookupSwitchLabels(int position, object? constantValue)` looks for switch labels available at the current position. This requires that the position be within a switch statement. When the constant value is specified, a specific case label with the specified constant value is searched, otherwise, all available switch labels are returned. If not within a switch statement, an empty collection is instead returned.

`GetSwitchDefaultLabel(int position)` returns the default label within the switch statement enclosing the current position. If not within a switch statement, or no default label exists, `null` is returned.

The two counterparts replacing the `int position` parameter with the `SyntaxNode switchStatement` parameter, consider the current position as the start of the span of the node. Those are the two methods that the position-based ones rely on.

We may also not include the methods containing the position parameter and instead only include the ones taking the `SyntaxNode` parameter. They were only proposed based on their more generic counterpart, `LookupLabels(int position, string? name)`.

## Usage Examples

``` C#
var defaultLabel = semanticModel.GetSwitchDefaultLabel(node.SpanStart);
if (defaultLabel is not null)
{
    // evaluate that all the other paths exhaust the possible cases
    var caseLabels = semanticModel.LookupSwitchLabels(node);
    foreach (var caseLabel in caseLabels)
    {
        var definition = caseLabel.DeclaringSyntaxReferences.First().GetSyntax();
        // determine if it is a relational expression label, if we are evaluating numeric literals
    }
}
```

## Notes

While switch case labels are very flexible in C#, allowing all kinds of patterns, including simple relational ones, or type / deconstruction / property-matching patterns, this API does not intend to cover all kinds of analysis, for both complexity and performance reasons. Deeper analysis should be covered by specifically analyzing the underlying node declaring the case label.

## Alternative Designs

Currently, the above is achievable by getting the underlying syntax of the symbol and comparing the syntax node's properties in a language-specific context. While not a great concern, providing a language-agnostic interface that also simplifies basic information retrieval is appealing.

## Risks

Bloating the public API with rarely-used functions.

Currently, it is an error if user applies `RequiresLocationAttribute` to a parameter, but it's not an error if user applies it at other places. This is consistent with for example `ParamArrayAttribute`, but not with for example `IsByRefLikeAttribute`.

@AlekseyTs says in https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/68871#discussion_r1254439062:

> let's confirm with LDM whether we want proactively prohibit application of the attribute in other contexts in order to preserve future design space.

Example:

[SharpLab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:)

```cs
using System;
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;

[RequiresLocation] // currently no error, has no effect here
[ParamArray] // no error, has no effect here
[IsByRefLike] // error, use `ref struct` instead
public struct C
{
    public void M(
        [RequiresLocation] // error, use `ref readonly` instead
        [ParamArray] // error, use `params` instead
        [IsByRefLike] // error, although it has no effect here
        int p)
    {
    }
}

namespace System
{
    class ParamArrayAttribute : Attribute { }
}
namespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices
{
    class RequiresLocationAttribute : Attribute { }
    class IsByRefLikeAttribute : Attribute { }
}
```
